Observation Details: Stopped to look at a Rock Pigeon sitting on Long Point Road, as they aren't common in this area. The bird was banded, with a blue plastic CU band issued by the Canadian Racing Pigeon Union (rather than a metal one from the Canadian Wildlife Service). The bird appeared slightly disoriented, perhaps by the local magnetic anomalies present along both shores of Prince Edward Bay amounting to about 3 degrees easterly on the south side and 3 degrees westerly on the north side - AKA "The South Marysburg Vortex"! Or it might have the H5N1 bird flu. Or maybe just having a kip.

Media notes: Rock Pigeon (Feral): “Pied Brown” plumage
Observation Details: I saw Louis Hoeniger’s eBird photo of a particularly interesting Pied plumage pigeon, with “Brown” as its base plumage selection.  Wanting to see the bird for myself (photo #4 below), I was happy to spy the bird before we even parked the car.  “Pied” refers to white mottling.  The site offered a second brown & white bird as well, but this one limited white to a more formal stripe up the front of its head and on to the crown.  A full “Brown” Adult was also found.  I decided to include pictures of all three birds, simply because Pigeons are often relegated to my “skip” folder, and this is a nice look at small differences from bird to bird.

Observation Details: This afternoon a sooty/dark pigeon alighted in the yard and fed on birdseed.  First and only time in over 25 years that a rock pigeon actually alighted and stayed in the yard [and even sat on the neighbor's roof for numerous spells].   Perhaps only the 4th record for the houselist, with the others mere fly-by's.  Potentially a "spread morph".  A pigeon expert wrote me in an email: "That one is pretty unique.  I doubt it came from far since it looks to be still in juvenile plumage and fairly recently weaned.  It's color is definitely unusual and I'm going out on a limb to guess here.  Just from the pics, it MIGHT be a Tiger Grizzle in juvenile plumage.  If you look at the shots you have of the wing, you can see whitish color at the base of the shield feathers.  I had a youngster somewhat like this some years back and it molted out into a mottled bird.  Individual black/white feather in a somewhat random pattern all over the bird."  Frank Mosca at:  bluecheck2@lycos.com  Also, see these checklists:  https://ebird.org/ak/view/checklist/S8707644 and https://ebird.org/ak/view/checklist/S8710407

Media notes: Possibly pure ancestral rock pigeon?
Observation Details: In suitable habitat flying on an isolated stack on a craggy coastline. With a clean plumage, it would appear possible for this to be a 'purebred' individual but I don't know whether this would ever be possible to establish given the presence of many other rock pigeons with obvious domestic traits. Either way, they are filling the same ecological niche that ancestral rock pigeons would have done thousands of years ago.

Observation Details: Interesting observation! As I was jogging down Main Street, I saw a waking pigeon sitting on the curb, well into the night. Finding this to be a rather odd nocturnal observation of pigeon, I glanced back around, having just passed the bird, only to see it flying towards me! I put my arm out to block the bird’s passage and to my surprise it alighted gently thereupon, and cooed softly twice! The bird and I stayed together for some time and the saga went on quite a bit longer than indicated above, but I will spare you the details. I assume this was some sort of “little peep” scenario, but cannot be sure.

Media notes: Rock Pigeon (Feral) –“Brown” adult
Observation Details: I saw Louis Hoeniger’s eBird photo of a particularly interesting Pied plumage pigeon, with “Brown” as its base plumage selection.  Wanting to see the bird for myself (photo #4 below), I was happy to spy the bird before we even parked the car.  “Pied” refers to white mottling.  The site offered a second brown & white bird as well, but this one limited white to a more formal stripe up the front of its head and on to the crown.  A full “Brown” Adult was also found.  I decided to include pictures of all three birds, simply because Pigeons are often relegated to my “skip” folder, and this is a nice look at small differences from bird to bird.

Observation Details: Incredibly, this appears to be the last living Rock Pigeon in Whitehorse -- the Yukon's only established population. It wasn't too many years ago when there were 400 to 500 Rock Doves in Whitehorse; now there is just one, maybe two. Predation by Northern Goshawks and Common Ravens have driven the population to the edge of extirpation.

Estimated

Out of nowhere a completely white dove flew in from behind me and to my right. I caught note of its color thinking gull but its flight pattern was not that of a gull. I watched this white bullet artistically fly in wide circles with acute cuts of up and down repeatedly for 4 loops around SP…wishing it would land but it headed back towards SB and out of sight. Really a marvel to watch it fly..like no other I have seen..pigeons tend to fly in flocks and in smooth wide circles this little acrobat just owned the air. I ran into another birder Paul and said did you see that white dove..and he said are you sure its not a barn owl…it flew so much like a raptor..I showed him my pic and we both marveled how we had never seen such a show of flight skill before

They are not timid at all and came very close to people, but tend to fly away after a loud saund or a sudden movement. They are together all the time and if they are scared or something, they flew away in a big flock. Also, some birds made quiet gooey calls gu-gu-gu, gu-gu-gu and when they had enough of foraging, they flew on the nearby building's roof.
